HEADWORD: Obscuration
<hw>Ob`scu*ra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>obscurativ</ets>: cf. F. <ets>obscuration</ets>. See
<er>Obscure</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos> ]</ety> <def>The act or operation of
obscuring; the state of being obscured; <as>as, the <ex>obscuration</ex>
of the moon in an eclipse</as>.</def> <rj><au>Sir J.
Herschel.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

